EITS: Support for desktop email clients. Generative AI is tiring.

EITS: More experienced FT support staff at the IT helpdesk to supplement student workers and more quickly resolve the complex problems. Those take too much time when the IT desk is staffed by students alone.
COMMENT: Thanks for all you do!

EITS: My concerns are sometimes dismissed in ITS tickets. I understand computers very well. I can troubleshoot basic problems. So I get a little miffed when ITS suggests I clear my cache or restart the machine without taking me seriously.
ELS: More access to peer-reviewed publications, which are essential for my research. Maybe the world would be better if more things were open access, but I don't make the rules!
COMMENT: Thanks for all you do to support teaching and research at the College! I know there are many uphill battles. I am grateful for my library and ITS staff. Please let the faculty know if we can be helpful to you.

EITS: Sometimes it seems like my Helpdesk tickets languish and I'm not sure if anyone is following up. This has happened when I have issues on weekends, so it's understandable.
ELS: When I submit Library Acquisitions requests related to my teaching, I sometimes feel like I'm sending my Google-formatted request into the void.  On a couple of occasions, I have had to follow up with additional queries.  On another note, I LOVE ILL.

EITS: Aside from the Jupyter Hub that Will Amidon is spearheading, and perhaps the need for more video recording systems in more classrooms, I would like to see ITS offer and support a high-end computing version of the office laptop (for the 4-year cycle).
ELS: The most important service that the library offers is the interlibrary loan (particularly for electronic articles).  I have overall been very happy with this service, and it is important that it continues to be adequately staffed for rapid response.
COMMENT: In both our 200-level and 300-level physics lab courses, we ask students to do data processing in Python.  I have been using Google Colab for this because it allows students to work with data files stored in a shared Google Drive folder and can be run from the browser.  This keeps me from having to do any troubleshooting of installations on individual computers, and it lets me de-bug students work from anywhere because I have access to their files in the shared drive.  I have been sharing templates with students to get them up to speed.  A couple years ago, I had inquired about a Jupyter Hub, but it sounded like it was never going to happen.  I since got set up with Google Colab and have had a good experience with it.  However, there are certain interactive visualizations that it cannot do, so it might be nice to be able to customize things in a Jupyter Hub.  For our department, we would absolutely need to be able to have students be able to upload files and keep them in their own folder that persists throughout the term.  If Google were ever to pull their support of Google Colab (which they have been known to do with some of their services), then our courses would suffer greatly.

EITS: I get wildly different system responses when I plug my laptop into various rooms. Sometimes display and sound vary widely and there is no information about how to fix or adjust these things.  Also want a magic button to turn off classroom wifi
ELS: hire more librarians, integrate them more effectively into departments.

EITS: Quite frankly, nothing comes to mind that is within the control of ITS.
ELS: It's clear that the library is suffering from overly tight budgets. I am so deeply impressed with how library staff has worked to overcome these limitations, but I fear that it is not sustainable. My hope is that more resources are invested soon.

COMMENT: TOOOOO Long

EITS: It would be great to have just one "go-to" person for certain types of problems. I have encountered problems that simply required someone to just look at my account. The ticket system was confusing
ELS: More support for some of the databases/journal free subscriptions would be great, but for journals I can request individual sources through ILL, which I think is working well for me.

EITS: Prioritize faculty needs, not administrative projects -- for example, cut the huge amount of DLINQ resources dedicated to online teaching since we do not teach online classes. Faculty should guide priorities to be implemented by ITS, not the reverse.
ELS: Focus on needs from faculty, not internally-driven projects. As one of many examples, nobody uses the public open-access database because it is not needed, but it still has consumed extensive staff resources, displacing important academic needs.
COMMENT: To attract and retain employees, we need to pay Library and ITS staff better, but for the institution to do be able to do so, we need to make their work more efficient. This means discontinuing many activities that are not needed, so that staff labor can be focused on the essentials. As faculty members, it is our job to be experts on pedagogy in our discipline and the associated technology and reference resources. We need Library/ITS to support the implementation of these elements in our teaching and research. We don't need to have Library/ITS staff, who do not teach classes or conduct research and are not accountable to our students, formulate approaches that faculty are then supposed to "align" with, or act as shadow faculty carrying out research in pedagogical design. Having administrators with little or no actual expertise or experience in actual teaching or peer-reviewed research dictate their vision to faculty is both counterproductive and inappropriate, but unfortunately is often prioritized at the expense of staff who are working very hard to support the actual needs of faculty and the institution.

EITS: I wish we had on site training in qualitative databases like Nvivo. I would also benefit by training in website and digital scholarship. These are often offered during the semester when I am overloaded in my schedule. If there were broadleaf retreats
ELS: More study carrells available to faculty (my office is on the north facing side of a basement and I need more light!). More librarians with digital skills manning the ship on site so that faculty and students can drop in with a project and connect
COMMENT: Special Collections is my go-to, most valued place on campus and very important to my teaching and scholarship!!    Coming from UVA, I miss having a faculty-student community hub of digital scholarship--with a staffed, physical location in the library!!

EITS: Can you gives us a way to search only for books in MIDCAT from the get go rather than having to enter a search first and then limit it to books? Without that function you get a bunch of online reviews of the book you want, not the book. It's tedious.
ELS: Continuation of above. University of Amsterdam library has such function on its splash page if you want to see what I mean. Same system, but clicking on a button limits your search to books in the library's collections. https://uba.uva.nl/en/home
COMMENT: This survey was way too long.

EITS: I would love to have human being support for IT in MBH. I much prefer working with a person in person when I am having a struggle with a computing issue.
ELS: I have had many issues with accessing journal articles through the links from a Scopus or Pubmed search. I have not tried the system with the new library catalog process.

EITS: More staffing of the IT helpdesk with professional staff relative to student staff
COMMENT: I answered some questions with my students, rather than myself, in mind. If you're also surveying students directly, this might skew certain results. For example, how interested I am in library instruction is largely on behalf of my students.

ELS: I'm relatively new but feel I'm not sure what current services include, so I'm not taking advantage of them.  They were explained during new faculty orientation, but an update now that I have my feet under me would be helpful.
COMMENT: In the offer of workshops or instruction, I have the interest in learning more, but not the time.  There are so many things happening at Middlebury, and as a faculty member of low rank, they all seem like things I must do to advance.  This isn't a problem for your program to solve, but it's worth keeping in mind that any lack of engagement is likely due to factors beyond your control.  Thank you!

EITS: Maintain access to help desk

A laminated, one page, instruction sheet secured firmly to the wall next to each classroom's system. Old school, simple, clear. No scanning necessary to solve, don't need a cell phone to scan a code. Each room is different, gets frustrating.
ELS: Hard to say b/c each year needs change.  Sometimes, a research project requires a lot of library help. Then, I can go 5 years needing more tech help but not librarian help. Then, its about JSTOR. Next semester about accessing room tech. Flexibility!
COMMENT: I appreciate your effort to be responsive. The hard part is that you are trying to plan ahead and direct limited resources where needed and, in my case, I am never quite sure from year to year what I am going to be working on. Overall, I do not work with big quant data sets and I am, actually, very old school in my teaching in a lot of ways. I like to read important texts with students and talk and write about them. Canvas and Google Docs are extremely important and useful--I use both every day and depend on them for many kinds of collaborations with colleagues and students.

EITS: Perhaps a new computer a year earlier. At the current 5-year schedule I find my computer struggles over the finish line. Also, when I remember the last time I got a new computer it was enormously stressful to set it up, and time consuming.
ELS: The jewels of the library are the special collections and the IT infrastructure on campus to help us work in our offices, at home, and in classrooms. I appreciate all the work that goes into making our work go smoothly.

EITS: Perhaps staff the HelpDesk with staff (as opposed to Work-Study students) who have expert information on Mac computers. I have been frustrated in the past by the lack of knowledge of some of the students.
ELS: I'm relatively happy with library services here at Middlebury. I find the news system recently put in place quite good; I have found sources with ease, and been able to request books through inter-library loan.

EITS: WiFi in Twilight Hall has been patchy in the past year. It didn't use to be like that (both in offices and classrooms).

ELS: More staff positions---and support (compensation) for existing library staff.

EITS: I'm satisfied with what you're doing now.

EITS: It has been quite a few years since I had any complaints about IT services!  Maybe put more people on the Help Desk... but I fully understand staffing problems.
ELS: Please retain all databases and eBooks!  When these were suddenly eliminated a few years ago, it quickly became a massive problem both for me and for my students.  Now they are all back and I wouldn't want to lose them again.
